Denise, I want to get back to you on your comments on the Ukraine War and what I think you are missing.
Russia’s redline has always been former Soviet Republics and Warsaw pact nations can not join NATO. Gorbachev, Yeltsin, Putin and the old Soviet Guard were and are staunch supporters of this policy. But even before the Soviet Union was formed, Mother Russia’s foreign policy was always about controlling extensive land area that protect Mother Russia from outside forces.  The agreements noted were simply an extension of this historical fear of Europe but of Asia as well.  With this as background, the US agreed to this fault line, perhaps informally, but nevertheless agreed, if Russia guaranteed the independence of these post-Soviet independent nations.  Russia agreed. Indeed, Ukraine gave up its nukes as part of this agreement. Professor John Mearsheimer, one of the world most famous strategic thinkers on global politics agrees and makes the case you are making Denise that the Ukraine War- taking of Crimea in 2014 and the attack in 2022, were all related to NATO crossing the redline. Noam Chomsky also blames NATO. You and Noam are strange bedfellows indeed.
Well, the redline was crossed long before 2014 when in 2004 seven nations were admitted into NATO including the Baltic states- Estonia, Lithuania and Latvia. Russia did nothing then. Why? Because it was going through an economic crisis of its own and more importantly Putin did not have the dictatorial power he had in 2014.  Putin’s consolidation of political power allowed him to create the largest kleptocracy in history and the Russian people are paying the price. Bill Browder, at one time the largest foreign investor in Russia, and the architect of the Magnitsky Act, which authorizes the U.S. government to sanction those foreign government officials worldwide that are human rights offenders, freeze their assets, and ban them from entering the U.S., knows Putin the best. Denise, listen to this YouTube clip piped.us.projectsegfau.lt/watch?v=0VIlQrx-…
Browder’s point is that the Ukraine War has almost nothing to do with crossing a redline but everything to do with Putin stealing a trillion dollars from the Russian people resulting in a collapsing economy. His fear that the Russian people will turn on him as a result led him to aggressively attack Ukraine and in the process directing the anger of the Russian people to an outside enemy- Ukraine supported by the Western elites- rather than the enemy within-Putin.
I know Browder is telling the truth about Putin. In 1991, I had the opportunity to work with Estonian government officials and academics on economic issues facing the fledgling Estonian democracy. I spent 10 days in Estonia seeing the damage the Soviets did to this nation. But all the people I met, from the average Estonian to the President all had the same fear of the Russian Bear. Remember, Estonia is a stone’s throw from St. Petersburg. So the attack on Ukraine is nothing more than Putin carrying out a Ukrainian genocide to save himself and his oligarch supporters. In my view the US has a moral responsibility to support Ukraine. This war is not primarily about NATO expansion.
What should a US led NATO do? What is in the American national interest? I always turn to economics first. If my view is correct, Putin will not stop at Ukraine. If one runs this scenario out, the European continent is at risk, and of course trade with the US and foreign investment is at risk. War is politics by other means, and in this case Putin’s objective is resource control. Letting Putin win is detrimental to the American national and economic interests. On this basis alone we should support Ukraine and declare this loud and clear.
Should we fear a nuclear conflict?  Of course, we should. But you need to remember why the war started to begin with. Putin and the oligarchs want to protect their wealth. Starting a nuclear conflict does not achieve this objective.  Like the US, Russia has a nuclear protocol. Putin does not walk into a room and push a button and BOOM. He needs agreement and he will never get it in my view.  This is especially true if it is clear to the Russian leadership- the old guard and the oligarchs- that the use of tactical nukes will end the world as they need it.  What is the outcome? The Ukraine military pushes the Russians out of most of Ukraine. Putin is removed or killed. The new leadership- mostly the old guard and the oligarchs- enters negotiations the basis of which guarantees Ukrainian independence.
